<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-12-13T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-12-13T15:00:00-05:00" n="252" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d252">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12–1148: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-12-13T15:00:00-05:00">December 13, 1948—3
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1812. Urtel 2501 Dec 11. In conversations with Madame Chiang both
                            President and Secretary have expressed sympathy with Chinese
                            difficulties but have not given any indication of any change in US
                            position and have made no commitments beyond implementation present
                            China Aid Program.</p>
                        <p>For your info neither Amb Koo nor any other Chi official was present
                            during Madame’s conversation with President.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>